    Numpy

    NumPy¶

    Numpy is a python library that supports multi-dimensional arrays and a large collection of mathematical functions. It is a super powerful library that is compatible with all different types of other libraries such as machine learning libraries.

    The question might be, why are we using NumPy instead of python's basic functions? The reason is that numpy are densely packed arrays of homogenous types like uint8 or float16. Additionally, python arrays use pointers for objects, while NumPy uses no pointers instead uses reference.

    Typically, when the equation becomes more complex the more resources it will consume. Using basic python functions can overwhelm the computer very fast very easily. To perform a mathematical operation, python needs to loop through all the objects within the array while NumPy can perform it at once.

    In this notebook we will follow the CRUD operations - Create, Read, Update, and Delete - to summarize all the most basic functionalities of Pandas.

    Table of Contents¶

    • Install: How to install and import numpy
    • Create: how to create a numpy array
    • Read: how to read a numpy array or a value in an array
    • Update: how to manipluting an array or a single value
    • Delete: delete an array within an array

    Install numpy¶

    Some of the computers might haven't numpy pre-installed on the machine. One of the methods to install the library is to use !pip install

    In [1]:
    Copied! 
    !pip install numpy
    !pip install numpy
    Requirement already satisfied: numpy in /usr/local/lib/python3.7/dist-packages (1.21.5)

    After successfully installing the library we can import it. It is commonly used the abbreviation of numpy as np.

    In [2]:
    Copied! 
    import numpy as np
    import numpy as np

    Create¶

    Random Arrays¶

    We can create an array with random numbers by using the randint() and rand(). The difference is that the first one will create an array with integers, while the other with floats.

    • integer: random.randint(low, high=None, size=None, dtype=int) to create an array with random intergers
    • float: random.rand(d0, d1, ..., dn) to create an n-dimensional arrays of floats
    In [3]:
    Copied! 
    # Array with random 10 integers between 0 and 5 (excluded)
random_ints = np.random.randint(5, size=10)
random_ints
    # Array with random 10 integers between 0 and 5 (excluded) random_ints = np.random.randint(5, size=10) random_ints
    Out[3]:
    array([4, 2, 0, 1, 3, 1, 1, 0, 1, 2])
    In [4]:
    Copied! 
    # Array with random floats
random_floats = np.random.rand(1, 2, 3)
random_floats
    # Array with random floats random_floats = np.random.rand(1, 2, 3) random_floats
    Out[4]:
    array([[[0.23016933, 0.88748874, 0.94096517],
        [0.25275991, 0.2290442 , 0.26646432]]])

    numpy.zeros(shape, dtype=float, order='C', *, like=None) allows to create a zero function with a single or multiple dimensions

    In [5]:
    Copied! 
    # Array of 0s with the given dimension
zero = np.zeros((3, 2, 1))
zero
    # Array of 0s with the given dimension zero = np.zeros((3, 2, 1)) zero
    Out[5]:
    array([[[0.],
        [0.]],

       [[0.],
        [0.]],

       [[0.],
        [0.]]])

    numpy.full(shape, fill_value, dtype=None, order='C', *, like=None) is used for creating an array that is filled with a single number

    In [6]:
    Copied! 
    # Array of a specific number with a specfic shape
full = np.full((2, 2, 2), 4)
full
    # Array of a specific number with a specfic shape full = np.full((2, 2, 2), 4) full
    Out[6]:
    array([[[4, 4],
        [4, 4]],

       [[4, 4],
        [4, 4]]])

    Unlike full(), ones() will fill the array with 1s

    In [7]:
    Copied! 
    one = np.ones((2, 2, 2))
one
    one = np.ones((2, 2, 2)) one
    Out[7]:
    array([[[1., 1.],
        [1., 1.]],

       [[1., 1.],
        [1., 1.]]])

    Custom Array¶

    To create a custom array we can use the function array(). This function can also be used to convert a python array into a numpy array

    In [8]:
    Copied! 
    array = np.array([[1, 2, 3], [3, 2, 1]])
array
    array = np.array([[1, 2, 3], [3, 2, 1]]) array
    Out[8]:
    array([[1, 2, 3],
       [3, 2, 1]])

    Let's convert an existing array into a numpy array

    In [9]:
    Copied! 
    # Create an array 'a'
a = [[4, 5, 6], [7, 8, 9], ['a', 'b','c'], [1.0, 2., 3.33]]

# Convert '' into a numpy array
data = np.array(a)

print(f"a has a type of {type(a)} | np_a has a type of {type(data)} ")
    # Create an array 'a' a = [[4, 5, 6], [7, 8, 9], ['a', 'b','c'], [1.0, 2., 3.33]] # Convert '' into a numpy array data = np.array(a) print(f"a has a type of {type(a)} | np_a has a type of {type(data)} ")
    a has a type of <class 'list'> | np_a has a type of <class 'numpy.ndarray'>

    Read¶

    Attribute¶

    We can inspect an array in many different ways. One of the methods is to use attributes. For instance,

    • shape: get the dimension of an array
    • size: get the total number of values in the array
    • dtype: get the type of the values in the array

    Previously we have created a random array. We will use that array to visualize the attributes.

    First, let's recall the data array.

    In [10]:
    Copied! 
    data
    data
    Out[10]:
    array([['4', '5', '6'],
       ['7', '8', '9'],
       ['a', 'b', 'c'],
       ['1.0', '2.0', '3.33']], dtype='<U32')

    Not, let's display those attributes.

    In [11]:
    Copied! 
    # Attributes
a = data.shape
b = data.size
c = data.dtype

# Print the result
print(f" shape: {a}\n size: {b}\n dtype: {c}")
    # Attributes a = data.shape b = data.size c = data.dtype # Print the result print(f" shape: {a}\n size: {b}\n dtype: {c}")
     shape: (4, 3)
 size: 12
 dtype: <U32

    As we can see above, the shape of the data array is 3x4. It has 1 value in the array and the values have a type of <U32. A <U32 stands for the set of lower case Unicode 32 character

    Slicing¶

    Slicing is used for getting values out of a NumPy array, for example

    • data[0]: to get the first array
    • data[0:2]: get the array between 0 and 2, but exclude array 2
    • data[-1]: get the last array
    • data[2][1][0]: get the first value ([0]) of the array [1] and [2]
    In [12]:
    Copied! 
    # Slicing
array = data[0]  # get the first array
slicer = data[0:2]  # get the array between 0 and 2, but exclude array 2
reverse = data[-1]  # get the last array
single_value = data[2][1][0]  # get the first value ([0]) of the array [1] and [2] 

# Print the result
print(f" array: {array}\n slicer: {slicer}\n reverse: {reverse}\n single_value: {single_value}")
    # Slicing array = data[0] # get the first array slicer = data[0:2] # get the array between 0 and 2, but exclude array 2 reverse = data[-1] # get the last array single_value = data[2][1][0] # get the first value ([0]) of the array [1] and [2] # Print the result print(f" array: {array}\n slicer: {slicer}\n reverse: {reverse}\n single_value: {single_value}")
     array: ['4' '5' '6']
 slicer: [['4' '5' '6']
 ['7' '8' '9']]
 reverse: ['1.0' '2.0' '3.33']
 single_value: b

    Update¶

    Before starting this section let's quickly two random arrays that we will use to demonstrate the methods in this part.

    In [13]:
    Copied! 
    # Create two arrays with random integers
a = np.random.randint(5, size=5)  # numbers between 0 and 5
b = np.random.randint(5, 10, size=5)  # numbers between 5 and 10

# Display array a and b
a, b
    # Create two arrays with random integers a = np.random.randint(5, size=5) # numbers between 0 and 5 b = np.random.randint(5, 10, size=5) # numbers between 5 and 10 # Display array a and b a, b
    Out[13]:
    (array([1, 3, 4, 1, 4]), array([8, 9, 5, 6, 5]))

    Basic Math¶

    • np.add(): adding arrays
    • np.subtract(): subtracting arrrays
    • np.divide(): dividing arrays
    • np.multiply(): muliplying arrays
    • np.dot(): dot product of two arrays

    Those are the basic mathematical functions that we will illustrate.

    In [14]:
    Copied! 
    # Basic Math
add = np.add(a, b)
sub = np.subtract(a, b)
div = np.divide(a, b)
mult = np.multiply(a, b)
dot = np.dot(a, b)

# Display results
print(f" add: {add}\n sub: {sub}\n div: {div}\n mult: {mult}\n dot: {dot}")
    # Basic Math add = np.add(a, b) sub = np.subtract(a, b) div = np.divide(a, b) mult = np.multiply(a, b) dot = np.dot(a, b) # Display results print(f" add: {add}\n sub: {sub}\n div: {div}\n mult: {mult}\n dot: {dot}")
     add: [ 9 12  9  7  9]
 sub: [-7 -6 -1 -5 -1]
 div: [0.125      0.33333333 0.8        0.16666667 0.8       ]
 mult: [ 8 27 20  6 20]
 dot: 81

    Statistical Functions¶

    Next, let's explore some basic statistical functions.

    • np.sqrt(): square root of a number
    • np.abs(): absolute value of a number
    • np.power(): the power of a number
    • np.log(): muliplying arrays
    • np.exp(): dot product of two arrays
    • np.min(): minimum value of a set of numbers
    • np.max(): maximum value of a set of numbers

    Note: numpy has a lot of mathematical functions available to use, for more visit NumPy.

    In [15]:
    Copied! 
    # Statistical functions
sqrt = np.sqrt(81)
abs = np.abs(-9)
power = np.power(2, 10)
log = np.log(9)
exp = np.exp([9])
min = np.min(a)
max = np.max(b)

# Display results
print(f" sqrt: {sqrt}\n abs: {abs}\n power: {power}\n log: {log}\n exp: {exp}\n min: {min}\n max: {max}")
    # Statistical functions sqrt = np.sqrt(81) abs = np.abs(-9) power = np.power(2, 10) log = np.log(9) exp = np.exp([9]) min = np.min(a) max = np.max(b) # Display results print(f" sqrt: {sqrt}\n abs: {abs}\n power: {power}\n log: {log}\n exp: {exp}\n min: {min}\n max: {max}")
     sqrt: 9.0
 abs: 9
 power: 1024
 log: 2.1972245773362196
 exp: [8103.08392758]
 min: 1
 max: 9

    Update a value in an array¶

    So far we have manipulated an entire array. We can also change a single value.

    Let's quickly create a random array with integers

    In [16]:
    Copied! 
    # Create array
data = np.random.randint(9, size=(2, 2))

# Display array
data
    # Create array data = np.random.randint(9, size=(2, 2)) # Display array data
    Out[16]:
    array([[4, 6],
       [5, 3]])

    Changing a single value in the data array

    In [17]:
    Copied! 
    # Original value
ori = data[0][0]

# Change a single value
data[0][0] = 99

# Display results
print(data)
print(f"original: {ori}, new: {data[0][0]}")
    # Original value ori = data[0][0] # Change a single value data[0][0] = 99 # Display results print(data) print(f"original: {ori}, new: {data[0][0]}")
    [[99  6]
 [ 5  3]]
original: 4, new: 99

    Why not sort the number in the array by using sort() function. By default, it will be sorting the numbers from the lowest to the highest value.

    In [18]:
    Copied! 
    # Sort
data.sort()

# Display result
data
    # Sort data.sort() # Display result data
    Out[18]:
    array([[ 6, 99],
       [ 3,  5]])

    We can also reshape the dimension of an array by using the function reshape().

    In [19]:
    Copied! 
    # Original shape
data.shape
    # Original shape data.shape
    Out[19]:
    (2, 2)
    In [20]:
    Copied! 
    # reshape
new_data = data
new_data = new_data.reshape((1, 1, -1))

# Display result
new_data.shape, new_data
    # reshape new_data = data new_data = new_data.reshape((1, 1, -1)) # Display result new_data.shape, new_data
    Out[20]:
    ((1, 1, 4), array([[[ 6, 99,  3,  5]]]))

    Append¶

    append() is to add a value at the end of the array

    In [21]:
    Copied! 
    # Original array
a = np.array([1, 2, 3])
print(f"Original: {a}")

# Append
a = np.append(a, [4])
print(f"New: {a}")
    # Original array a = np.array([1, 2, 3]) print(f"Original: {a}") # Append a = np.append(a, [4]) print(f"New: {a}")
    Original: [1 2 3]
New: [1 2 3 4]

    Insert¶

    insert() is to insert a value into a specific position in the array.

    In [22]:
    Copied! 
    # Original array
a = np.array([1, 2, 3])
print(f"Original: {a}")

# Append
a = np.insert(a, 0, 9)
print(f"New: {a}")
    # Original array a = np.array([1, 2, 3]) print(f"Original: {a}") # Append a = np.insert(a, 0, 9) print(f"New: {a}")
    Original: [1 2 3]
New: [9 1 2 3]

    Delete¶

    numpy.delete(arr, obj, axis=None) will delete a specific axis of an array

    • arr: specify the input array or the array to alter
    • obj: location within an array that should be deleted
    • axis: the axis that should be deleted 0 for column and 1 for row
    In [23]:
    Copied! 
    # Create a random array of integers
d = np.random.randint(10, size=(3,3,3))
d
    # Create a random array of integers d = np.random.randint(10, size=(3,3,3)) d
    Out[23]:
    array([[[9, 9, 2],
        [3, 2, 1],
        [8, 4, 8]],

       [[8, 8, 6],
        [6, 2, 7],
        [2, 2, 2]],

       [[1, 2, 9],
        [6, 9, 8],
        [9, 0, 2]]])
    In [24]:
    Copied! 
    # Delete
e = np.delete(d, 0, axis=1)
e
    # Delete e = np.delete(d, 0, axis=1) e
    Out[24]:
    array([[[3, 2, 1],
        [8, 4, 8]],

       [[6, 2, 7],
        [2, 2, 2]],

       [[6, 9, 8],
        [9, 0, 2]]])
